<li id="cite_note-74"><b><a href="#cite_ref-74" title="">^</a></b> Carey, James W. "Harold Adams Innis and Marshall McLuhan" in <i>McLuhan Pro and Con</i> (1969) Baltimore: Pelican Books, p. 281. Graeme Patterson strongly disagrees with this view arguing that Innis paid an extraordinary amount of attention to perception and thought, while McLuhan examined institutions. Both Innis and McLuhan, Patterson argues, were preoccupied with language, one of humanity's basic institutions. See Patterson, pp.36-37.</li>
<li id="cite_note-75"><b><a href="#cite_ref-75" title="">^</a></b> Watson, pp. 410–11.</li>
<li id="cite_note-76"><b><a href="#cite_ref-76" title="">^</a></b> McLuhan, Marshall. (2005) <i>Marshall McLuhan Unbound.</i> Corte Madera, CA&#160;: Gingko Press, v.8, pp. 5–8.</li>
<li id="cite_note-77"><b><a href="#cite_ref-77" title="">^</a></b> Carey, (McLuhan Pro and Con), p. 271.</li>
